bug.short_desc: [emfWorkbench] Editmodel needs to specify a workspace scheduling rule for save

long_desc.thetext: In case of projects that are checked into sourcecontrol, the entire workspace needs to be locked before a save happens to a resource. In org.eclipse.wst.common.internal.emfworkbench.integration.EditModel, we are passing the project as the scheduling rule, which needs to be changed to specify the workspace.
Created an attachment (id=52056) Patch that passes in the workspace as the scheduling rule to the save operation
approve

I approve - this was the behavior in V6 (we defaulted to workspace root).
Although I agree it doesn't make sense for the CC(or pessimistic adapter) to lock the entire workspace.. regardless we need to prevent this rule scope collision.

To provide some more background and information on this defect:
This problem is seen when using the Clearcase Pessimistic Adapter as well as the CC Remote Client (CCRC). When a save on a resource is attempted (in this case, the EAR project's application.xml), the following check is performed in ThreadJob.push(), which is eventually called from File.setContents(InputStream, int, IProgressMonitor) :
baseRule.contains(rule) (This method is called )
where 'baseRule' is the rule specified by us in EditModel.runSaveOperation, and 'rule'is specified by the source control adapter.
In the case of the Clearcase Pessimistic Adapter, the rule returned by the PessimisticResourceRuleFactory is always the workspace root. This causes the above check to fail, causing the exception below to be thrown, and failing the save operation.
In V6, we were not passing any rule to the save operation, which made it default to workspace root, and the comparison described above used to succeed. However, in wtp, we are now explicitly passing the Project for the baseRule, which causes the above check to fail.
In order to fix this, we are now passing the workspace root as the scheduling rule to the save operation.

bug.short_desc: Publish fails when Server w/o initial status is started

long_desc.thetext:
Env't: ====== Eclipse 3.2.1 WTP 1.5.1
Scenario: ========= 1. Server is created and project (vanilla dynamic web project) is added, presumably from a previous session (eg. the day before). 2. Server is configured to auto-publish on start. 3. Workbench is launched -- server status is not known (correct behaviour). 4. Server is currently stopped, so user starts the server.
Errors: ======= 1. Receive error dialog before server completes startup. "Publish is not performed since the server is not started. Start the server before performing the publish operation."
2. Noticed that while server status was in "Starting...", the server state went to "Publishing...". The tool does not seem to be waiting for the server to complete startup before attempting to publish.
3. .metadata/.log contents: !ENTRY com.ibm.ws.ast.st.common.core 4 0 2006-10-11 16:36:28.654 !MESSAGE Publish is not performed since the server is not started. Start the server before performing the publish operation.
Workarounds: ============ 1. Initialize the server status before trying to start it. This is a usability hit since it requires the user to perform several more mouse clicks than necessary.
Analysis: ========= After sticking some debug code and enabling various traces, I think the problem is in org.eclipse.wst.server.core.internal.Server::synchronousStart(String mode2, IProgressMonitor monitor).
There is an internal anonymous IServerListener created whose sole purpose seems to be to listen for the completion of the server startup routine (and subsequently set a notify flag to true). However, it seems that the listener also listens for IServer.SERVER_STOPPED events in addition to IServer.SERVER_STARTED events -- not sure why.
This is a problem b/c when the initial server status is not known. This is b/c before a start is attempted, the server status is discovered first. For this particular case, the result is that the server is stopped. This triggers a broadcast of a server event IServer.SERVER_STOPPED. The anonymous internal listener inside of org.eclipse.wst.server.core.internal.Server::synchronousStart(String mode2, IProgressMonitor monitor) picks up on this and sets the internal notify flag to true.
Further down in this method, there is a while loop that waits for several conditions before it breaks out. One of these conditions is whether or not the notify flag is true. Since it was set to true when the initial server status was discovered, this "waiting loop" doesn't wait at all and eventually the publish routines are invoked even tho the server has not finished starting-up. (FYI, other conditions include whether or not the user cancelled the start operation or whether or not the server timeout was reached... all of which are false according to debug statements).
If I modify the internal listener so that it only picks up on IServer.SERVER_STARTED events, then the publish only happens when the server is completely started. However, I'm not sure what impact this has on any other scenarios.
I would ask to see this fixed in WTP 1.5.1 even tho there is a workaround since this error is easily encountered and it occurs in several of our products. Let me know if you need further information. Thanks, Bevon
PS For my own referece, this bugzilla is cross-referenced with 392004.

Although this is minor bug, it is an ugly bug that causes the user to see error when the user just brings up the workbench and then hit the start button. Therefore, I am requesting to add to WTP1.5.2 hot list.

Created an attachment (id=52276) Patch to load behaviour delegate (syncs server state)
Defect confirmed. The problem is that when you bring up the workspace and try to start immediately, the server can be in an 'unknown' state and the start method fails. If you do another action first, such as add/remove projects or create a new server, it triggers the initial load of the server behaviour delegate that initializes the server's state, which avoids the problem.
The solution is just to load the server behaviour delegate before running these methods that depend on the state. If the delegate is already loaded this call does nothing. If the delegate is not loaded it loads the class and allows it to initialize the server state first, which would happen later in these flows anyway.
I've patched all three "start" methods on the server just to be safe. It's possible that other methods have the same problem (I will be checking them), but I beleive catching all the start cases is a good balance between fixing the obvious problem and not making unnecessary code change.
The patch has been tested by myself and the adopter and it solved the problem.
Requesting PMC approval for 1.5.2.
Patch looks simple.

Could you please provide a test case? What are the compiler settings for your project? This looks like a reconciling issue.

Is this change affecting only this project? I hope so. Thanks for the hint!

It looks like you want to use a method defined in the 1.5 libraries using the compliance 1.4. I don't see why you are doing this. In 1.4, you would need to do the boxing (wrapping the primitive types in their Wrapper type yourself). In 1.5 this is done for you by the compiler. However you won't be able to run this code on a 1.4 VM since the libraries in 1.4 don't contain the format method for the class java.lang.String. So I have two questions: 1) in your first comment, you said the program compiles ok. I would expect it to fail to compile. On the command line I guess you are using javac 1.5 which means you should set the compliance to 1.5 to get the same case in Eclipse. Using compliance 1.4 really means that you would use javac 1.4 to compile the corresponding code. And this would not compile either. 2) I guess you really want the compliance to be 1.5 if you are using the String#format(...) method. Otherwise you will end up with NoSuchMethodError at runtime on a 1.4 VM.

bug.short_desc: memory leak when doing post-compile time weaving

long_desc.thetext:
If you weave (post-compile time) a large number jars within the same ant invocation (without forking) you will reliably get a "java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: PermGen space". I
This was tested with Java 1.5.0_09-b01, AspectJ nightly from 10-11-2006 and 1.5.2.
Test case is an ant build script that just weaves a jar (log4j.jar) and then deletes the output jar in a loop. After 31 iteration I get the OutOfMemory error. The aspect that I'm weaving is just a simple tracer aspect with a join point doesn't even match the classes in the log4.jar.

Created an attachment (id=52072) zip file that contains scripts to reproduce
Contains a zip file with an ant build script that will continually weave a jar and cause an OutOfMemory error. See contained readme.txt for other instructions.

Permgen problems indicate leaking classloaders holding onto classes. If I turn on -verbose:class and run your build.xml then I can see all the AspectJ classes are loaded many times (if we crash on the 15th iteration, I see they've been loaded 15times). If I remove the <antcall> in your xml and inline the iajc call at that point, I see the classes loaded once and the jar is woven fine any number of times (it is much faster too). This is all because <antcall> spawns a new classloader that is causing the reload of the whole compiler/weaver.
The problem is I can't determine if it is AspectJ that has an anchored classloader reference in static somewhere - I can't see how we could leak classloader references when not loadtime weaving.

So is it an Ant bug that after the antcall invocation the new classloader isn't released?
As an aside, knowing that it's the <antcall> that's was causing the problem, I was able to "inline" the <iajc> invocation by using the ant <macrodef> tag (learn something every day).
As a further aside, the way we're using a iajc is to do post-compile time weaving of numerous jars that have already been built. Right now there isn't a way with iajc to provide a list of jars and have each jar be woven in place.
investigate for 1.5.4 - whether there is something to document here or a particular level of Ant to prereq.

(In reply to comment #2) > Seems that if we solve this bug (want dynamic content on the wiki) then we > don't need a website anymore.
For many things, that is true. The remaining difference will be that the website can only be changed by committers whereas the wiki can be changed by anyone. So if a project team wanted to publish something as a document-of-record, they would use the website.

I agree. For example, for the Mylar project it's key that we have a web site with concise content that we control the editing of. We also need to control the navigation to keep it simple and usable. Then there is all the wiki content that we need to link in (e.g. FAQ, User Guide, Contributor docs) that grows thanks to community contributions.
We would really like to move more content to the wiki, but the thing that's blocking us is is that there is no project-specific navigation (bug 157707). At least from a project page usability point of view I see that as way more important than enabling dynamic content on the wiki pages. Please consider at least commenting on the corresponding bug 157707 because it seems like a very easy fix that will provide benefits across the board--i.e. make the navigation bar that Phoenix currently supports interoperate with wiki pages.

I understand what's requested here, but a Wiki isn't designed to support dynamic content -- much like a hammer is not designed to cut wood. It's a tool for a different purpose. We could similarly ask that Wiki supports mail, chat, voip and calendaring too, but again, that's not what a wiki is for.
I'd just like for us to consider using the right tool for the right job. We already have a tool for dynamic content, and IMHO, if pages require dynamic content, then they don't belong on the wiki in the first place.

IMHO, the idea that if we have a wiki which can do dynamic content, we won't need a website is silly. There's committer-editable content (like FAQs, readmes, guides, HOWTOs, meeting reports with TODOs, etc.) and there's mostly-static content, edited only by leads and PMCs (plans, project meta, presentations, etc.).
Two needs, two solutions.
Recommend marking this bug WONTFIX or INVALID.
That said, I'd still like to see the Wiki look more Phoenixy, but that's another story (see bug 163118). ;-)

bug.short_desc: Project with WTK Device Platform missing midp libraries in build path

long_desc.thetext:
Tested against M2
Create a Device Platform for WTK (either 22 or 23 beta is same behavior). Create a Runtime Platform for this device platform. Create a new MIDlet project, select the runtime platform and choose the Hello World template.
There are errors in the project, due to missing MIDP classes in the build path.
I believe this is because the midpapi20.jar file in WTK is not included in the build class.
I discussed this with Kevin, and it appears that there is an assumption made that all of the necesary cldc and midp classes are in the library identified for the configuration. This is not the case with WTK. There is a separate cldcapi11.jar for the configuration, and a midpapi20.jar for the profile. This is also the way UEI spec expects things, since the manifest for each jar file allows for a single configuration/profile/service API.
This worked in milestone 1 by coincidence. If you look at the mtj.project file you can see in milestone 1 that the midpapi20.jar file was discovered as a service API (for both a service api called "MIDP" and a service API for MMAPI). It was included in the build path for the wrong reason.
in M2 this seems to have been cleaned up, and now the midpapi20.jar is not included in the build path.
Arto added a profile to the device definitions, so this is now working.
I have verified this against Sun WTK 2.2 and Sprint Wireless Toolkit.

bug.short_desc: RFC: Improvements to the Projects page

long_desc.thetext:
The Projects page (http://www.eclipse.org/projects/) is the gateway to all sorts of information about the Eclipse projects. Unfortunately, it seems that I've designed it poorly and only a few people can find the information they are looking for. For example, did you know that you can find all the previous release review slides and IP logs? And a timeline of upcoming release? And detailed instructions of how to add the required project status reporting infrastructure to your project page? ... Probably not.
So I'm opening this Request For Comments about redesigning the Project page. What information should be there and how should it be arranged? Even more fundamental, who should the audiences for this page be?

Here are my two cents....
I think it suffers from not being focused on a particular audience. It seems to have a lot of the Eclipse process stuff that is aimed ot the committers, the review/proposals aimed at the community, council stuff and then general links to the top-level projects that don't really seem to provide much value.
I would suggest that when people select the 'Project' tab there are three main audiences: 1) new people to Eclipse hoping to find informaiton (newsgroup, wiki, home page, download, etc) about a particular project, 2) project committers that need to find information about the development process etc. and 3) people that follow the Eclipse processes and are interested in the reviews/proposals/ip logs etc. IMHO, I would guess #1 is the highest traffic and #2 would be second.

(In reply to comment #1) I agree that the profiles outlined in comment #1 probably represent most of the accesses. One minor detail I disagree on is that the audience (1) doesn't necessarily include only people "new to eclipse", but also developers experienced with some eclipse projects interested in finding out more about Eclipse. I think I am a member of this audience, and one possible improvement I would suggest is to feature on the Projects page a tree graph showing all the projects in their place in the hierarchy. It could be a dhtml thing or some flash, whatever works. Also, I would like to see the summarized timeline featured more prominently - maybe it could occupy the space where we find the proposals table today.
Just some thoughts...

I couldn't quite figure out a tree of projects, so I used an indented list. I also moved the background verbiage to other pages via the "explain" links. I like the result - not quite "Google" in simplicity, but more useful than the previous projects page. http://www.eclipse.org/projects/
I'm working my way through the rest of the /projects/* urls and the /proposals/ pages as well.

I like the table. I have two suggestions:
- I think the column headings should be the complete word, because a) you have room for it and b) the abbreviations weren't obvious.
- You have the entire right column of unused real-estate that can be used to explain the icons. It wouldn't make the page any more complex, but would require less brainpower to figure out the icons, and that would save users a click.
BTW, it would have been nice for you to follow the Phoenix publishing guidelines: http://www.eclipse.org/phoenix/development.php

2) I agree with Denis that the column headings need to be complete words.

bug.short_desc: TransactionChangeRecorder doesn't remove itself

long_desc.thetext:
The TransactionChangeRecorder adapter adds itself to new Resources and EObjects as they are added to a resource set. There's not much documentation about what it listens to and for what period of time, but I would expect that whenever it adds itself to a Notifier, the inverse event should cause it to remove itself. This does not happen. For example: * Adding a resource to a resource set causes the adapter to be added to the resource and all contained EObjects; however, removing that resource from the resource set does not cause the adapter to remove itself from those objects. * Adding the adapter to an object (e.g. a resource) indirectly adds the adapter to all of the contents of that object (e.g. the contained EObjects). However, removing the adapter from the parent objects does not cause it to remove itself from the children.
This limitation is quite frustrating, as it forces client code to be have knowledge of this particular adapter and its modus operandi so that it can be explicitly cleaned up properly.
This bug was observed in the June-end Callisto release; I'm not sure what EMFT version number that corresponds to; sorry.

The TransactionChangeRecorder inherits the ChangeRecorder's property of being "sticky". Change recorders, in general, do not remove themselves in response to the reverse of the change that added them, because they need to continue recording changes to objects while they are detached from the model, in case they should be re-attached later (e.g., by undoing via ChangeDescription.applyAndReverse).
What a ChangeRecorder is able to do, however, is to remove itself from all of its targets when it is dispose()d. Unfortunately, this is difficult for the TransactionChangeRecorder, because it does not track its targets (an optimization). The TransactionalEditingDomain works on the premise that it controls the complete lifecycle of the model that its resource set contains. i.e., it assumes that you would never want to remove a resource from its resource set unless you're unloading it, in which case all adapters are removed from all of its contents when their proxy URIs are set.
Perhaps what is needed is to provide a utility that will do whatever is needed to remove an object or resource from an editing domain's control (requiring that it is already detached). Might that meet your requirement?

Re: comment #1: Yes, such a utility would be very helpful. Presumably, such a utility would also solve bug #161168, which I also filed recently.
As an aside, it would be very helpful if there were more documentation regarding the assumptions that editing domains make about their resource sets and the contents of those resource sets. (Such as, that an editing domain seems to assume that its resource set is not shared with anyone else, and as you say, that it owns and manages the complete lifecycle of everything inside.) These assumptions have a very deep and fundamental impact on the way that an application handles files and the references between them, and without this documentation, developers are left to deduce the intended behavior through trial and error.
I'm curious what you mean when you say that it is difficult for a TransactionChangeRecorder to remove itself when dispose() is called, because TransactionalEditingDomainImpl does just that.

Yes, this is exactly the kind of information that is planned for the next EMFT Transaction release (in line with Eclipse 3.3/Europa), in which we are planning to provide a more complete Developer Guide documentation.
TransactionalEditingDomainImpl.dispose() disposes its change recorder because ChangeRecorder.dispose() is a public API, which can be extended by clients that extend the transaction API. In the M5 milestone of GMF 1.0, for example, there was a specialization of the editing domain that provided a custom change recorder, which had additional stuff to clean up.
A new utility for removing the change recorder from a resource set would be used in a TransactionChangeRecorder.dispose() implementation to do what it currently doesn't. The problem today is that the implementation inherited from ChangeRecorder doesn't work because the TransactionChangeRecorder doesn't keep track of its targets. This can be improved by finding all of the objects currently in the editing domain's resource set, to remove the recorder from them, but this doesn't account for the objects that are no longer attached.

For objects that are no longer attached, these can be handled lazily. When the TransactionChangeRecorder of an editing domain that has been disposed receives an event from one of its targets, it can simply ignore the event and remove itself from its target at that time. This will ensure that the change recorder is at worst innocuous and cleans up objects that are still in use.
Est.: .5w

Created an attachment (id=54674) Proposed fix
Attached is a patch with changes to the TransactionChangeRecorder and a new TransactionUtil.disconnectFromEditingDomain() API that makes it possible to move Resources and model elements from a transactional editing domain to another editing domain (transactional or otherwise).
For examples of how to use it, please see the new JUnit tests (included in the patch).
Rick, would you be able to have a look at this patch to let me know whether it meets your requirements?

Committed the proposed fix to HEAD, with a few tweaks to ensure that:
- the change recorder forgets its editing domain, to allow it to be reclaimed by GC even if the recorder lingers on free-floating objects
- the disconnectFromEditingDomain() API accounts for the possibility of an object being in the control of multiple domains simultaneously (although this is much discouraged)

bug.short_desc: JarPackageFragmentRoot slow to initialize

long_desc.thetext:
We noticed a performance regression in WTP that when a J2EE project contains a server container classpath which has large jars on the classpath, the project cache seems to take long to initialize and each project takes around the same time to initialize although they share the same container classpath.
To give some numbers, I noticed that per project, JarPackageFragmentRoot.initPackageFragToTypes is being invoked 60,000 times (usually triggered by the first IJavaProject.findType or even some validators in WTP). This calls String.charAt 3.5million times and 300,000 times String.subString. This converts to around 800ms to 1s per project on my machine.
A thought which I am not sure whether its feasible or not is that since in WTP, most of the J2EE projects get the classpath entries from the same container (server), is it possible to have some kind of cache based on server container? As a result, this expensive operation does not need to be carried out on a per project basis.

1. What is the Eclipse build ID where you saw the regression ? 2. What is the last Eclipse build ID you saw it was 'fast' ? 3. What is the exact scenario you got the numbers from ? 4. What are the steps to reproduce the slowness ? 5. Can you elaborate on the caching stategy ? What values do you suggest to cache ? 6. Have you tried giving more memory to Eclipse (-vmargs -Xmx1024m) ? This should increase the internal Java model cache.
Created an attachment (id=52263) Screen capture on the call stack for my pop up action

To be investigated during M7.
One possibility is to find an already initialized project that uses the same external jar and use its cache to calculate the package fragments of the project being initialized.

(In reply to comment #4) > One possibility is to find an already initialized project that uses the same > external jar and use its cache to calculate the package fragments of the > project being initialized. Unfortunately, if another project's cache has already been initialized, the package fragments information is not easily available and thus would cost more to retrieve (would have to walk the other project's cache and for each package fragment find out if it is of the same root).
Another option is to force the caching of the root if it is shared by more than one project. In this case chances are that it will be reused.

bug.short_desc: [api] Transfer the full control of system type actions and state handling to the system type contributor

long_desc.thetext: With RSE 1.0, the complete state handling and life-cycle for system types are hidden within RSE. A contributor of a system has no chance to prevent things from happening (like connect on node expand). This is bad. Still it is a good idea to have default actions and life-cycle management for every system type or subsystem to allow easy startup, but it should be also possible for contributors to take over the complete handling of the nodes (starting with the system type node) in terms of states/life-cycle [delegates], context menu actions [delegates], toolbar actions [delegates] and label and content providers [delegates].

It looks like one step in the direction of allowing contributors more control over the system types has been done with the addition of the dynamic systemTypeContributor extension point (bug 172662).
Since the extender is now able to register a systemTypeContributor, he can return a specialized systemType class (e.g. MySystemType implements IRSESystemType). This allows him to also register a corresponding AdpaterFactory and Adapter (MySystemTypeAdapter extends RSESystemTypeAdapter) where at least the isEnabled() method can be overridden to allow for dynamic enablement.

Part of the work has been done by fixing [176481]. SystemViewConnectionAdapter is only adding actions being approved by the system type provider via RSESystemTypeAdapter. The default implemention is to accept always all actions except those actions which had been conditions associated already within the original implementation.
Uwe do you think this can be marked fixed since your recent changes? Can you add references to related bugs you fixed into the "depends on" field?
Yes. This is done now. With recent changes the dynamic system type provider can gain full control of the system type actions without loosing any of the default RSE ones.

bug.short_desc: Unicode problems in ProcessClosure.java
Function beforeDrawLegendItem(){} only works for Bar, Area, Meter, Pie, Stock Chart

long_desc.thetext:
The funtion works for all the chart types when LegendItemType is CATEGORIES_LITERAL.
However, if LegendItemType is SERIES_LITERAL, the function doesn't work for Line, Scatter, Bubble, Difference and Gantt Charts. Because all of these charts use markers as legend graphics, which changes accordng to the marker settings.

For Line, Scatter, Bubble, Difference and Gantt charts (LegendItemType = SERIES_LITERAL): The dynamic bounds will not distort the markers in the legend, so the chart engine will compare the width and height of bounds, and use the smaller one to compute the graphics. If the smaller figure is less than zero, then use the actual marker size instead.
For LegendItemType = CATEGORIES_LITERAL: Originally the graphics is always a square and only height setting can change its size. With the fix, the graphics displays as a rectangle, and both width and height takes effect.
Handle the corner case: If the smaller one between width and height of bounds is less than or equal zero, manually set markerSize = 1.
